## Playback and queue correctness

Define and test exact semantics for:

* Playing a selected item.
* Starting a context.
* Queue precedence.
* “Play next” versus “add to queue.”
* Previous after manual selection.
* Previous after a context switch.
* Natural track completion.
* Repeat one, repeat context, and repeat off.
* Shuffle stability.
* Reshuffle.
* Removing the currently playing or next track.
* Source failure.
* Local file disappearance.
* Remote stream failure.
* Seeking unsupported content.
* End of context.
* Switching modes while playing.
* Application exit and restart.
* Restoring state.
* Playback process cleanup.

No status bar may show one track while the audio backend plays another.

Use fakes and deterministic clocks/random seeds for transport tests.

## Performance requirements

The TUI must remain responsive during:

* Startup.
* Large-library loading.
* Search.
* Playlist synchronization.
* Lyrics retrieval.
* Playback startup.
* Cache writes.
* Network timeouts.
* Provider failure.

Measure baseline and final behavior with representative fixtures.

At minimum, detect:

* Blocking work in the render/input loop.
* Excessive cloning or full-library scans on every frame.
* Unbounded channels or queues.
* Repeated provider requests.
* Repeated parsing or index reopening.
* Excessive redraws.
* Leaked child processes.
* Unbounded caches or history.
* Slow terminal-width calculations.
* Work repeated when state has not changed.

Use defensible performance budgets based on measurement. Record before-and-after results. Do not claim “fast” without evidence.

